# Project context

This is a full-stack Kanban task tracker built as a portfolio/interview
project, not a disposable prototype. It is deliberately built to production
standards: typed end-to-end, tested, containerized, deployed to Kubernetes.

Stack: NestJS + Prisma + PostgreSQL (backend), Next.js App Router + Zustand +
dnd-kit (frontend), Socket.io (realtime), Docker + Kubernetes (deploy).

See `PROJECT_PLAN.md` at the repo root for the full phased plan, including a
"Hunt for" note per phase — a specific edge case to deliberately find and fix.
When implementing a phase, read its "Hunt for" note and treat it as a
requirement, not an afterthought.

# How to work with me

- I am a senior frontend-leaning full-stack engineer, strong in React/
  TypeScript, competent but not deep in backend — deepening NestJS skills on
  purpose. Explain backend-specific NestJS/Prisma idioms briefly when you
  introduce them; don't explain basic JS/TS/React concepts.
- Prefer explicit code over clever abstractions. I will be explaining every
  part of this codebase in interviews — don't generate anything I can't
  defend line by line.
- When you make an architectural choice with real trade-offs (e.g. optimistic
  locking vs fractional indexing, cookie vs header auth), state the
  alternatives and why you picked one, in a short comment or in your reply —
  not silently.
- Never silently swallow errors. Every catch block either handles the error
  meaningfully or rethrows with context.
- Do not add a library or dependency without saying so explicitly and why it's
  needed over what's already installed.

# Code style

- TypeScript strict mode everywhere. No `any` unless justified with a comment.
- Prefer small, single-purpose functions/modules over large ones.
- Environment variables are read only through a typed config module, never
  `process.env.X` scattered through business logic.
- No secrets, tokens, or credentials committed — use `.env` (gitignored) and
  keep `.env.example` up to date whenever you add a new variable.
